This not only confirms that some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widely spread, but provides more details than fossils, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
According to scientists, the plumage of this animal was brown brown in the upper part, with a pale or carotenoid coloration in the lower part.
The discovery also allows to obtain detailed information about the evolution of the feathers.
Since the plumage of the dinosaur is not equipped with the basic structure, the so-called rachis, but instead has other characteristics typical of feathers, beards and beards, the researchers concluded that the rachis is probably the result of an evolutionary development following such characteristics.
The plumage structure suggests that it was not used for flight, but rather for temperature adjustment or courtship. The researchers hypothesize that, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the find shows an adult plumage and not the chick down.
