Technological determinism is a term that includes in practice a wide range of ideas, from technological innovation or technological imperative to the strict sense that the fate of man is driven by a underlying logic, associated with scientific laws and their realization in technology.
Much of the interpretation of technological determinism has two general ideas in common: one is that the development of technology itself follows a path that goes far beyond political and cultural influence, and the other is that technology has in turn “effects" on societies that are intrinsic, rather than socially conditioned.
For example, we can say that the car necessarily involves a development of the road network.
However, a national road network for only a few cars is not economically sustainable, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the costs associated with car ownership.
Mass possession of cars also leads to a greater percentage of accidents on the roads, and consequently the invention of new rescue techniques for the care of injured people.
