For a primate with a digestive system similar to that of human beings, it is difficult to meet its own need for amino acids with the plant resources available in the savannah.
In addition, failure to carry out such activities has serious consequences: slowing growth, malnutrition and, ultimately, death.
The most easily accessible plant resources would have been the proteins present in leaves and legumes, but for primates like us they are difficult to digest, except they are cooked.
Animal foods (such as ants, thermites, eggs) are not only easy to digest, but they provide a high amount of protein containing all the essential amino acids.
In light of all this, it should come as no surprise that our own ancestors have solved their “protein problem” in a certain sense as the savannah chimpanzees do today.
Sleep interruption is the intentional awakening process that occurs during the normal sleep period, followed by a recovery of sleep (10–60 minutes later).
