Sundarbans are the largest coastal mangrove coastline in the world. It extends for 80 km (50 mi) from the coast inland to Bangladesh and India.
The Sundarbans have been declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The part of the forest included in the Indian territory is named Sundarbans National Park.
However, the forests are not just mangrove marshes: in them there is also what remains of the imposing jungles that once covered the Ganga plain.
